  "heading": "Data Sharding",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "text": "Data Sharding is a database technique in which large data is divided into smaller parts, called shards, and stored across multiple servers."
    },
    {
      "text": "Each shard contains only a portion of the total data."
    },
    {
      "smallHeading": "Simple definition"
    },
    {
      "text": "Data sharding is the process of splitting a database into smaller, faster, and more manageable parts to improve performance and scalability."
    },
    {
      "line": true
    },
    {
      "mediumHeading": "Why do we need Data Sharding?"
    },
    {
      "text": "When data grows very large:"
    },
    {
      "list": [
        "One database becomes slow",
        "Too many users access it at the same time",
        "Server gets overloaded"
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "**Problems without sharding:**"
    },
    {
      "orderedList": [
        "Slow queries",
        "Limited scalability",
        "High server load",
        "Single point of failure"
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "ðŸ‘‰ Sharding solves these problems"
